\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 1  Background\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Neutron scattering is a non-destructive analytical technique which can be used to investigate certain physical properties of materials and thin films in a similar fashion as the better-known field of X-ray scattering. I will add a few applications over here. What differentiates neutron scattering from X-ray scattering is the interaction with the investigated material. When X-rays interact with the electron cloud, neutrons are interacting with the nucleus of atoms. While the basic principles of these techniques are the same, this difference in interaction has profound consequences for the potential possibilities for neutron scattering. The penetration depth of neutrons for instance is much larger than for X-rays, enabling the study of bulk materials. Another important advantage is the possibility to measure the magnetic properties of materials using neutron scattering, which can not be done with X-ray techniques. The scattering properties for neutrons vary significantly for each isotope, whereas the scattering properties for X-rays depend on the density of the electron cloud. This makes the combination of X-ray and neutron scattering a very powerful technique, as it gives rise to two completely independent data sets with the same structural information. This latter advantage is exploited in this report, where we use a combination of X-ray and neutron scattering in order to find the structural properties of deposited multilayers. The dawn of neutron scattering began in the first half of the twentieth century. The first experiments on Bragg reflection using neutrons were conducted as early as 1936. In order to do proper condensed matter research, one needs a high enough neutron flux, however, which was not possible until the end of the second world war with the invention of nuclear reactors. Neutrons cannot be generated from a filament in the same way as photons can, traditionally they are instead produced using nuclear fission. For this process, Uranium-235 is used as fuel. When a neutron collides with Uranium-235, it releases on average 2.4 neutrons. One of these is used for a new collision with a Uranium-235 particle, leaving another 2.4 neutrons to be used for neutron scattering experiments. A particular challenge with this technique is the availability of Uranium-235, which is a byproduct of nuclear weapons. This means that the required material is not only scarce, but also very sensitive to political developments. A slightly newer technique is the use of so called spallation sources. In these sources, proton pulses are accelerated to high energies, typically in the range of GeV, and directed onto a target. Upon collision, about 10 to 20 neutrons are expelled which can be used for neutron experiments. For both techniques, the neutron energy is too high for experiments. In order to reduce the energy of the neutron beam, the neutrons are transferred through a so-called moderator material such as H2O. This slows the neutrons down, and thereby reduces their energy such that they can be used for neutron scattering experiments. Include a sentence to say that in order to transport and handle the neutrons from the source to the experiment we need a neutron guide.
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_neutronbookmatrac \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{neutronbookmatrac}}}
]\par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 2  Neutron multilayers\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Neutron multilayers are used in many different neutron optical instruments. One example of this are neutron guides, which hare used to guide the neutron beam itself. A neutron guide consists of different neutron supermirrors, which are made using a multilayer containing many different periods. Multilayers are also used for monochromators, which are used to select specific wavelengths of a beam. By choosing a certain period at a specified angle, only one wavelength fulfills the Bragg condition at reflection. Meaning only a certain wavelength will be reflected at the specified angle. This technique is commonly used to filter specific wavelengths. Using magnetic multilayers, one can also make a neutron polarizer. Once the layers are magnetized, there will be a different optical contrast for spin-up and spin-down neutrons. With the right set of materials, only one spin-reflection will be reflected while the other spin direction will be transmitted. The resulting beam here will be in one spin-direction only. Such a polarized beam can be used to investigate the magnetic properties of a material. Interface width of multilayers and the current state-of-the-art The performance of multilayers in terms of reflected intensity is highly dependent on both the optical contrast and the interface width between the layers. The optical contrast is limited by the materials of choice, while the interface width can be reduced using the correct deposition techniques. The lowest interface width that can be achieved in the current state-of-the-art is about 7 \u195?\u8230?. Reducing this interface width has advantages for multiple applications. One of these are neutron supermirrors, which consists of a multilayer with many different periods. The reflectivity performance of a neutron supermirror depends exponentially on the achieved interface width. Meaning even a small improvement will lead to a drastic increase in reflectivity performance. This means that the total flux at experiment can be increased very significantly by improvement in instrumentation, without the need of more power-intensive neutron sources. The other advantage of a reduced interface width is that the minimum thickness that can be achieved is reduced as well. The total thickness of a layer cannot meaningfully be less than the width of the interfaces. If the interfaces can be made flatter and more abrupt, the layers can be made thinner as well. This means for example that monochromators for instance can be made for higher wavelengths and lower energies, such as cold neutron beams. \par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 3  Research aims\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 The essential goal of this work is to enhance the performance of neutron multilayers by reducing the interface width between the layers. As they are such essential and crucial elements in any of the intended neutron instrumentation, even the slightest improvements of the performance will have an immediate and large impact on all research conducted using those instruments. The work presented will have a significant focus on the simulation and modelling of neutron multilayers. The underlying goal here is to develop an understanding of the interface evolution of the samples, and how their performance is affected by different parameters. Finally, this project is part of the SwedNess neutron graduate school, which is established in the context of the European Spallation Source (ESS) which is being built in Lund. The overall goal in general is thereby also to develop an understanding of neutron scattering in particular, and thereby increasing the expertise that is needed with the planned operations of ESS in the future.\par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 4  Outline of the thesis\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 In this thesis we will start with the theoretical background behind the experimental work. Starting with Chapter 2, we will describe the general scattering theory. Where we will take a look at both neutrons and X-rays and where they differ. The multilayer optics are described in chapter 3, which will describe the reflection of different kind of multilayers and what they are dependent on. The deposition of the multilayers in this work are covered in chapter 4. Here we will also describe the sputtering techniques that are used to minimize the interface width between the layers. The instrumental aspects for the reflectivity are described in chapter 5. The reflectivity simulations, which are the main technique for the characterization of the structural parameters in this work, are described in chapter 6. The other multilayer characterizations, such as ERDA, XPS and TEM are covered in chapter 7. A summary of the results will be given in chapter 8, followed by an outlook in chapter 9. The summary of the papers in this work, as well as the papers themselves are covered in chapter 10 and 11 respectively. \par
