\pard\plain\s4\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\*\bkmkstart BMSLD}2.2{\*\bkmkend BMSLD}  Scattering length density\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 While the total scattering power of a single nucleus can be well described in terms of scattering length, in order to get a good measure of the total scattering power of a material we also need to take the physical density into account. If the nuclei are more tightly packed, there will be more nuclei per unit volume to scatter from, which inevitably leads to stronger scattering. The total scattering power of a material is therefore described in terms of scattering length density (SLD), which can be calculated by summing the scattering lengths of each element in the material and dividing this by the volume of the unit cell 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_neutronbookmatrac \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{neutronbookmatrac}}}
]: {\par
