\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 It can be extremely convenient in neutron scattering to describe phenomena in reciprocal space instead of real space. This convenience arises from the fact that the diffraction pattern is directly related to the reciprocal space of the SLD-profile of the material, so by becoming familiar with this description, one can tell a lot about the structural properties of a given multilayer simply from a glance at the obtained diffraction pattern 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_shinjo_takada_1987 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{shinjo\\s\\do5({\fs16 t})akada\\s\\do5({\fs16 1})987}}}
]. The reciprocal space corresponds to the Fourier transform of real space, and is often also called q-space or Fourier space. \par
