\pard\plain\s4\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb360 \fi0 4.2  Fourier expansion for an ideal multilayer\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 The intensity profile that is obtained by experiment is directly dependent of the SLD-profile in the probed direction, as explained in subchapter {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMneutronscattering \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{@TitleReference {2.1}{Neutron scattering}}}}. For a perfect multilayer with abrupt interfaces, the SLD-profile in the depth direction will have the form of a square wave. The obtained intensity profile can then be explained by the Fourier transform of this profile. The SLD-profile can be written as an infinite series of cosines and sines 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_kittel \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{kittel}}}
