\tab{\b0 (7)}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 Taking the derivative of the error function we get a Gaussian distribution: {\par
\pard\plain\s12\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqc\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\i f}({\i z})= \\F({\i d}{\i g},{\i d}{\i z})= \\F(1, \\R(,2{\u960*}{\u963*}\\s\\up5({\fs16 2}))){\i e}\\s\\up5({\fs16 \u8722? \\F(1,2)( \\F({\i z},{\u963*}))\\s\\up4({\fs13 2})})}}{\fldrslt }}
\tab{\b0 (8)}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 If we take the Fourier transform of a Gaussian we get another Gaussian. So the attenuation factor associated with our Fresnel equations can be described as {\par
\pard\plain\s12\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqc\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\f5\u771\'7e}{\i f}({\i z})={\i e}\\s\\up5({\fs16 \u8722? \\F({\i s}\\s\\up4({\fs13 2}){\u963*}\\s\\up4({\fs13 2}),2)( \\F(4{\u960*}{\u963*}{\plain sin}{\u920*},{\u955*}))\\s\\up4({\fs13 2})})}}{\fldrslt }}
\tab{\b0 (9)}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 This factor is known as the Debye-Waller factor and is commonly used to simulate imperfect interfaces. From this factor and combining it with Fresnel equations, we find that the reflectivity of a multilayer can be described as: {\par
\pard\plain\s12\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqc\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\i R}={\i R}\\s\\do5({\fs16 0}){\i e}\\s\\up5({\fs16 \u8722?(2{\u960*}{\i m} \\F({\u963*},{\u923*}))})}}{\fldrslt }}
\tab{\b0 (10)}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 Note that the reflectivity of a sample depends exponentially squared on the interface width. So even a modest improvement of the interface width has a large impact on the total reflectivity. The influence of the multilayer period can be explained by the fact that a multilayer with a smaller period has a larger fraction of the layer consisting of interfaces. The smaller the period, the more important the quality of the interface therefore becomes for a good reflectivity performance.\par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 3  Off-specular scattering\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 So far we have only considered the specular part of the reflection, where the angle of incidence is equal to the angle of refraction. For an ideal interface, the scattering potential in the in-plane direction is always constant, meaning all scattering will be in the specular direction normal to the plane of incidence. In the case of surface roughness however, local differences occur in the chemical composition of sample in the in-plane direction. This means that the parallel components of the neutron beam experience a potential barrier, leading to partial reflection in the in-plane direction. This phenomenon, where scattering occurs outside of the specular direction is is named off-specular scattering. This is further illustrated in figure {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMoff_specularsketch \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{@TitleReference {3.7}{An incoming neutron beam reflects from the sample and reaches the detector, the specular signal can be found in the plane of incidence while the off-specular signal is perpendicular to the plane of incidence.}}}}, where an incoming neutron beam reflects from the sample and reaches the detector, the specular signal can be found in the plane of incidence while the off-specular signal is perpendicular to the plane of incidence. Since off-specular scattering probes the in-plane direction of the interface, one can obtain a lot of information of the roughness profile of the interfaces. Interfacial roughness for example leads strong scattering potential barriers in the off-specular direction, and therefore increases the off-specular signal. Intermixing however leads to a much more gradual contrasts in the in-plane direction and contributes therefore much less to the off-specular signal. {\par
\pard\plain\s31\qc\sb120\sa0\keep\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi300  \par
\pard\plain\s9\qc\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0  \par
\pard\plain\s30\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 {Figure {\*\bkmkstart BMoff_specularsketch}7{\*\bkmkend BMoff_specularsketch}: An incoming neutron beam reflects from the sample and reaches the detector, the specular signal can be found in the plane of incidence while the off-specular signal is perpendicular to the plane of incidence.}{\field{\*\fldinst TC "7 An incoming neutron beam reflects from the sample and reaches the detector, the specular signal can be found in the plane of incidence while the off-specular signal is perpendicular to the plane of incidence." \\f f}{\fldrslt }}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi300 There are several parameters that influence the off-specular signal in a multilayer. The most important ones that we will describe here are the cross correlation length, the transverse correlation length and the Hurtz parameter. The cross correlation length of a multilayer describes how closely correlated the roughness profile is between the subsequent interfaces within the multilayer. This parameter is particularly interesting for this work, as correlated roughness means that deviations from an ideal layer at the interface repeat themselves for subsequent layers, meaning that such deviations may increase with each newly deposited layer. This phenomenon, which is called accumulated roughness, is a particular challenge when depositing multilayers with many periods as is conventional with neutron supermirrors for example.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Correlated roughness in a multilayer can be detected in the off-specular signal by looking at the so-called Bragg sheets. When the interface profile is completely uncorrelated, the off-specular signal scatters into different directions for each layer within the sample, meaning the off-specular signal will be spread out over the entire reciprocal plane. For completely correlated layers, the off-specular signal is scattered into the same direction for each layer. As the periodicity of this interface profile is the same as the multilayer period, this signal will be focused on in perpendicular sheets around the Bragg peaks of the specular signal. This is illustrated in figure {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMcorrelated_vs_diffuse \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{@TitleReference {3.8}{An incoming neutron beam reflects from the sample and reaches the detector, the specular signal can be found in the plane of incidence while the off-specular signal is perpendicular to the plane of incidence..}}}}\par
{\pard\plain\s31\qc\sb120\sa0\keep\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi300  \par
\pard\plain\s9\qc\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0  \par
\pard\plain\s30\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 {Figure {\*\bkmkstart BMcorrelated_vs_diffuse}8{\*\bkmkend BMcorrelated_vs_diffuse}: An incoming neutron beam reflects from the sample and reaches the detector, the specular signal can be found in the plane of incidence while the off-specular signal is perpendicular to the plane of incidence..}{\field{\*\fldinst TC "8 An incoming neutron beam reflects from the sample and reaches the detector, the specular signal can be found in the plane of incidence while the off-specular signal is perpendicular to the plane of incidence.." \\f f}{\fldrslt }}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi300 The latteral correlation length is sometimes described as the cut-off for the length scale where an interface begins to look smooth. The absolute magnitude of the interface width can very well be low, but the interface still looks very rough if the latteral correlation length is low enough. This is illustrated in figure {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMcorrelationlength \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{@TitleReference {3.9}{While these two multilayers have roughly the same interface width, the sample on the right-hand side looks much more smooth due to the higher latteral correlation length. The latteral correlation length describes the cut-off length scale where an interface begins to look smooth.}}}}, the latteral correlation length basically describes the typical distance between the peaks in this figure.\par
{\pard\plain\s31\qc\sb120\sa0\keep\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi300  \par
\pard\plain\s9\qc\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0  \par
\pard\plain\s30\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 {Figure {\*\bkmkstart BMcorrelationlength}9{\*\bkmkend BMcorrelationlength}: While these two multilayers have roughly the same interface width, the sample on the right-hand side looks much more smooth due to the higher latteral correlation length. The latteral correlation length describes the cut-off length scale where an interface begins to look smooth.}{\field{\*\fldinst TC "9 While these two multilayers have roughly the same interface width, the sample on the right-hand side looks much more smooth due to the higher latteral correlation length. The latteral correlation length describes the cut-off length scale where an interface begins to look smooth." \\f f}{\fldrslt }}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 Finally the Hurtz parameter describes the jaggyness of the interfaces in the sample. A sample with a Hurtz parameter of 1.0 looks relatively smooth where the interfaces gets more jaggy the closer the Hurtz parameters gets to zero. This factor shows mainly in the shape of the off-specular signal. A more ideal sample with low jaggyness shows a more Gaussian distribution in the off-specular reflectivity, where this shape becomes very Lorentzian for very jagged samples.\par
