\pard\plain\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs40\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 Chapter {\*\bkmkstart BMmultilayerdepositions}6{\*\bkmkend BMmultilayerdepositions}\par
\pard\plain\s2\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs40\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 Multilayer Depositions\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 In order to create high quality multilayers a proper understanding of the growth technique is necessary. In this chapter we will explain the techniques used to grow the samples discussed in this work, starting by an introduction on magnetron sputter deposition itself.\par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 1  Magnetron sputter deposition\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 One of the most popular techniques to grow multilayers is physical vapor deposition (PVD) 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_alvarez_garcia_martin_lopez_santos_rico_ferrer_cotrino_gonzalez_elipe_palmero_2014 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{alvarez\\s\\do5({\fs16 g})arcia\\s\\do5({\fs16 m})artin\\s\\do5({\fs16 l})opez\\s\\do5({\fs16 s})antos\\s\\do5({\fs16 r})ico\\s\\do5({\fs16 f})errer\\s\\do5({\fs16 c})otrino\\s\\do5({\fs16 g})onzalez\\s\\do5({\fs16 e})lipe\\s\\do5({\fs16 p})almero\\s\\do5({\fs16 2})014}}}
]. Magnetron sputter deposition is a common type of PVD, which is used to grow the samples in this work. The basic working principle behind sputtering is intuitively quite simple. A steady flow of noble gas is led into a vacuum chamber. Meanwhile, a bias is applied to the sputtering target, which contains the material that will be deposited upon the substrate. Stray electrons near the target are accelerated towards the substrate due to the electric field that is present, colliding with neutral atoms from inlet sputtering gas on the way. If these electrons have gained sufficient energy upon collision, it may knock off an electron from the sputtering gas, converting it onto a positively charged ion 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_ohring \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{ohring}}}
]: {\par
\pard\plain\s12\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqc\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {{\i e}}\\s\\up5({\fs16 \u8722?})+{{\i A}{\i r}}{\u8594*}2{{\i e}}\\s\\up5({\fs16 \u8722?})+{{\i A}{\i r}}\\s\\up5({\fs16 +})}}{\fldrslt }}
\tab{\b0 (1)}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 Note how two additional electrons are released during this ionization process, these too are accelerated by the electric field and can bombard additional gas atoms generating even more free electrons. Meanwhile the ionized atoms, which are positively charged, will be attracted to the negatively charged sputtering target. Upon collision, both target atoms as well as secondary electrons are ejected. The secondary electrons will be accelerated and ionize even more neutral gas atoms while part the ejected target atoms will land on the substrate surface, slowly creating a uniform layer of the target material. {\par
\pard\plain\s31\qc\sb120\sa0\keep\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi300  \par
\pard\plain\s9\qc\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0  \par
\pard\plain\s30\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 {Figure {\*\bkmkstart BMmagnetronsputtering}1{\*\bkmkend BMmagnetronsputtering}: A simplified sketch of magnetron sputtering. Incoming Argon ions collide upon the sputtering target, knocking out target atoms which in their turn form a new layer of the material on the substrate.}{\field{\*\fldinst TC "1 A simplified sketch of magnetron sputtering. Incoming Argon ions collide upon the sputtering target, knocking out target atoms which in their turn form a new layer of the material on the substrate." \\f f}{\fldrslt }}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 This state of ionized gas is known as a plasma, and is generally considered as an own state of matter. Upon the electron excitation of the sputtering gas, photons will be emitted which gives the visible plasma a visible glow. In order for the plasma to be sustained, there has to be a sufficient amount of collisions between electrons and sputtering atoms. So the secondary electrons are very important to sustain the plasma. 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_ohring \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{ohring}}}
].\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 In order to maximize the amount of secondary electrons that can be used for the ionization process magnets are placed behind the target material. The subsequent Lorentz force on the electron provides a path for the electrons to follow. A typical orientation of these magnets is shown in figure {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMmagnetronsketch \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{@TitleReference {4.2}{A cross section of a magnetron used in sputter deposition. The resulting magnetic field B traps secondary electrons which is sustain the plasma.}}}}, where the magnetic field is orientated radially above the target surface. The resulting path will follow a direction according to {{{\i E}}{{\i B}}}, forming circular trajectory above the target surface. Given the preferential status of this path for the electrons, the ionization rate will be higher in this region leading to a higher plasma density. It is for this reason that a circular erosion zone appears on used targets.\par
{\pard\plain\s31\qc\sb120\sa0\keep\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi300  \par
\pard\plain\s9\qc\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0  \par
\pard\plain\s30\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 {Figure {\*\bkmkstart BMmagnetronsketch}2{\*\bkmkend BMmagnetronsketch}: A cross section of a magnetron used in sputter deposition. The resulting magnetic field B traps secondary electrons which is sustain the plasma.}{\field{\*\fldinst TC "2 A cross section of a magnetron used in sputter deposition. The resulting magnetic field B traps secondary electrons which is sustain the plasma." \\f f}{\fldrslt }}\par
}\column
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb480 \fi0 2  Ion Assistance\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 In order to optimize the growth process and create smooth and abrupt layers, it is important to consider the energy of the incoming adatoms on the multilayer that is being deposited. When the adatom energy is too low, the surface mobility will be very limited meaning incoming adatoms will stick directly to their landing sites. Because of this, any deviation in the film surface will not be evened out but instead will be repeated. Such growth will therefore lead to rough surfaces with a lot of accumulated roughness 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_thesis_fredrik \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{thesis\\s\\do5({\fs16 f})redrik}}}
].\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Increasing the adatom energy will increase the surface mobility, adatoms that land on the surface can migrate to another spot, smoothening out the deposited layer. It is therefore important for a smooth film, to increase the adatom mobility. One way to do this, is to use the ions that are available in the plasma during film growth 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_thesis_kenneth \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{thesis\\s\\do5({\fs16 k})enneth}}}
]. By applying a negative bias on the substrate, there will be a significant potential drop towards the substrate meaning the ions will be accelerated towards the film. By controlling the bias on the substrate, the ion-atom ratio can be controlled such that there is enough energy per adatom to enable surface migration at the landing sites. These different cases of film growth are illustrated in figure {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMlayergrowth \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{@TitleReference {4.3}{The left side shows film growth with low adatom energy, adatoms stick directly to their landing sites leading to a rough surface. The right-hand side shows higher adatom mobility where surface migration is possible, ions are attracted from the plasma assisting the growth process.}}}}. {\par
\pard\plain\s31\qc\sb120\sa0\keep\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi300  \par
\pard\plain\s9\qc\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0  \par
\pard\plain\s30\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 {Figure {\*\bkmkstart BMlayergrowth}3{\*\bkmkend BMlayergrowth}: The left side shows film growth with low adatom energy, adatoms stick directly to their landing sites leading to a rough surface. The right-hand side shows higher adatom mobility where surface migration is possible, ions are attracted from the plasma assisting the growth process.}{\field{\*\fldinst TC "3 The left side shows film growth with low adatom energy, adatoms stick directly to their landing sites leading to a rough surface. The right-hand side shows higher adatom mobility where surface migration is possible, ions are attracted from the plasma assisting the growth process." \\f f}{\fldrslt }}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi300 However, the high-energy bombardments of ions can lead to intermixing at the interfaces, meaning particles of the film will be displaced into the substrate. Using a too high energy therefore leads to an increase in intermixing, which essentially has the same effect as regular roughness. It is therefore important to find a good balance between the smoothening effect due to surface migration at high adatom energies, and the lack of intermixing that comes with low adatom energies. The plasma can be guided using a magnetic field near the substrate, such that a lower ion energy is required for surface migration, there will however still remain intermixing between the two layers.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 While this intermixing effect is mainly limited to the first atomic layer, the multilayers in this work have an interface width that is roughly in the order of the atomic spacing. Such small displacements can therefore lead to a significant increase in the total interface width and should therefore be avoided.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 In order to achieve this, a so called split-bias scheme is used during the growth of the deposited multilayers. In this set-up, an initial layer is grown with a low bias at the substrate. This layer initial layer is therefore grown with a very low adatom energy, leading to relative rough growth at a lower density, but without any intermixing. After an initial part of the layer is grown using this low-bias scheme, the bias is increased in order to allow for surface migration when the adatom reaches the surface, smoothening the rest of the layer. While there will be intermixing at this higher bias, the intermixing will be limited to the initially grown layer which is the same material. The initially grown layer therefore acts as a buffer layer, to protect the lower layer against intermixing. This process with an alternating bias scheme is repeated throughout the deposition of the entire multilayer, leading to smooth and abrupt surfaces 
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_thesis_fredrik \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{thesis\\s\\do5({\fs16 f})redrik}}}
].\par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 3  {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C co-deposition\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 When growing multilayers using magnetron sputtering, nanocrystallites tend to form throughout the sample. These crystallites lead to rather faceted interfaces between the layers which can contribute to an increased interface width. Another risk is how intermetallics may form between the layers, which also contributes to an decrease in the abruptness between the layers. Furthermore, roughness patterns at the interface tend to be replicated leading to roughness accumulation. It would therefore be beneficial to eliminate the formation of crystallites, growing an amorphous multilayer instead. This can be established by co-depositing {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C during the growth process. The addition of boron to the layer inhibits the formation of crystallites, leading to X-Ray amorphous layers throughout the entire multilayer. Using a continuous deposition of {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C during the growth process, boron is added through the entire multilayer. For neutron multilayers it is important to consider that the the boron-10 isotope, which is present in natural boron, absorbs neutrons. The boron-11 isotope however is virtually completely transparent to neutrons, it is for this reason that an isotope enriched {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C target is used during the deposition. The power to the {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C magnetron is constant during the entire deposition, resulting in a stable {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C-flux during film growth. Note that the addition of {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C leads to a dilution of the SLD-contrast between the interfaces, adding too much {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C therefore leads to a reduction in reflectivity. The power that is used for the {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C-target is therefore tweaked such that it is high enough to make the entire sample is amorphous, but not increased any further to prevent unnecessary dilution in SLD-contrast between the interfaces. \par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 4  Reducing interface width\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 When designing high-performance neutron multilayers, it is essential to consider the interface width in the sample. A combination of the techniques above is used to minimize the total interface width as much as possible. The co-deposition of {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C removes all crystallinity of the multilayer. However, the adatom mobility during deposition is also significantly reduced leading to a strong accumulation of interface width throughout the layer. A high ion-assistance is therefore needed to increase the adatom mobility enough to allow for surface diffusion. These adatom energies however lead to a strong intermixing between the interfaces, making it essential to combine the {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C co-deposition with the split-bias ion-assistance technique. The resulting deposition scheme therefore incorporates the split-bias scheme as described in chapter 4.2. Where an initial buffer layer is grown with a low bias, followed by the rest{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C of the layer grown with a higher substrate bias. During this entire process, {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\up5({\fs16 11})}}{\fldrslt }}
}B{{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ \\s\\do5({\fs16 4})}}{\fldrslt }}
}C is co-deposited constantly throughout the multilayer to get inhibit the formation of crystallites. The bias used during the process needs to be fine-tuned, such that intermixing does not exceed the initial buffer layer, while being high enough to allow for surface diffusion.\par
