\pard\plain\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs40\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 Chapter \par
\pard\plain\s2\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs40\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 Instrumental aspects\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 In order to obtain structural parameters for the samples, the experimental reflectivity curves need to be fitted to mathematical simulations for each sample. There are several possible mathematical descriptions that can be used, within this work there are two different descriptions that are applied based on the software that has been used. Specular reflectivity is used described using the Paratt recursion formula, whilst the off-specular simulation is described using the Born-approximation. Both of these formalisms are described in this chapter.\par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 1  Neutron Reflectometry\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Neutron reflectometry is a popular technique to investigate structural properties of thin film multilayers. The physical principles behind this technique are described in chapter 2. There are two distinct ways to measure the scattering profile. The reflectivity in the reciprocal q-space can be calculated using the following expression: {\par
\pard\plain\s12\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqc\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\i q}= \\F(4{\u960*},{\u955*}){\plain sin}{\u920*}}}{\fldrslt }}
\tab{\b0 (1)}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Traditionally the incidence angle is changed in order to obtain the needed values for q. A challenge with this technique is how the spot size becomes infinitely large as the incidence angle approaches zero. A large portion of the beam does therefore not reach the sample, leading to a so-called beam overspill effect. This effect can be observed in figure {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMrawmeasurement \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{@TitleReference {5.1}{A simplified sketch of magnetron sputtering. Incoming Argon ions heat the sputtering target, knocking out target atoms which in their turn form a new layer of the material on the substrate.}}}}. {\par
