}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 Using relatively simple geometry and the beam profile, it is possible to calculate this effect and correct for this in the data. However, practice shows that a proper correction depends on a good alignment of the sample which can be a challenge. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 An alternative method to measure the intensity profile is to not change the incidence angle, but to change the wavelength. This does require an incoming neutron beam with a wider variety of wavelengths. As the energy of a neutron can be described as E = hv/lambda, the wavelength of a neutron is directly dependent of its velocity. Specific velocities can be selected using so-called fermi choppers. These are rotating disks placed with a certain distance from eachother with a small opening where neutrons can pass, as sketched in figure X. These disks rotate with a certain angular velocity, such that only specific velocities of neutrons can pass between both disks. These fermi choppers therefore act as a velocity filter, and therefore using E = hv/lambda as a wavelength filter. By varying the wavelength during measurement and keeping the incidence angle constant, one can obtain the requested range of q using equation X, without having any beam overspill effects.\par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 2  Neutron Instrument\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 The instrument used in this work for neutron measurements is a monochromatic reflectometer operating at a neutron wavelength of 5.21 \u195?\u8230?. A sketch of the instrument can be seen in figure X. The actual setup at the experimental site is divided up with a physical wall. The incoming neutron beam arrives through the waveguides at the left-hand side of the wall (as seen in the sketch), and the beam subsequently moves from the monochromator crystal where a single wavelength is selected towards the detector on the right-hand side in the sketch. The polarizer that is used in this reflectometer acts simultaneously as a wavelength filter, the polarizing functionality is not used however since this work is limited to unpolarised neutron reflectometry.\par
