\tab{\b0 (2)}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 It follows from this description that this formalism is recursive, the reflectivity of layer j+1 is required to calculate the reflectivity of the j\rquote th layer. To solve this equation, we can use {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\i T}\\s\\do5({\fs16 1})}}{\fldrslt }}
} = 1 and {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\i R}\\s\\do5({\fs16 {\i N}+1})=0}}{\fldrslt }}
} as starting point, this equates to the incident wave having full transmission at {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\i T}\\s\\do5({\fs16 1})}}{\fldrslt }}
}, and to no reflection from the substrate at {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\i R}\\s\\do5({\fs16 {\i N}+1})}}{\fldrslt }}
}. This formalism is commonly used to simulate the specular reflection for neutrons and X-rays in reflectivity simulation software. \par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 {\*\bkmkstart BMbornapproximation}2{\*\bkmkend BMbornapproximation}  Born Approximation\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 The Born approximation (BA) was proposed as early as 1926 by Max Born. To get to this approximation, we may first start with the general time-independent Schr\u195?\u182?dinger equation: {\par
\pard\plain\s12\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqc\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ ( \\F({\u295*}\\s\\up5({\fs16 2}),2{\i m}){\f5\u8711*}\\s\\up5({\fs16 2})+{\i V}({{\i r}})){\u936*}({{\i r}})={\i E}{\u936*}({{\i r}})}}{\fldrslt }}
\tab{\b0 (3)}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 We can re-write this as: {\par
