\pard\plain\s4\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 2.1  The Distorted Wave Born Approximation\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 When the scattering intensity becomes very large, the assumption of a planar wave in the conventional BA no longer holds, scattering entities themselves can introduce perturbations into the field and the wave therefore needs to be described as a distorted wave, a superposition of a downwards and upwards travelling planar wave. This is the underlying principle of the Distorted Wave Born Approximation (DWBA), which is the formalism that is used to simulate off-specular scattering in this work. The described wave function has a distorted form that can be described as downward and upward travelling waves for both the scattered and incident waves: {\par
\pard\plain\s12\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqc\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\u968*}\\s\\do5({\fs16 {\i w}})({{\i r}})={\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 \u8722?,{\i w}})({{\i r}})+{\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 +,{\i w}})({{\i r}})\\,{\i w}={\i i}\\,{\i f}.}}{\fldrslt }}
\tab{\b0 (11)}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 Where {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 \u8722?,{\i w}})}}{\fldrslt }}
} describes the downwards wave while {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 +,{\i w}})}}{\fldrslt }}
} describes the upwards wave. The relevant scattering elements can then be described using Dirac notation as follows: {\par
\pard\plain\s12\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqc\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {{\u968*}\\s\\do5({\fs16 {\i i}})}{{\u948*}{\i v}}{{\u968*}\\s\\do5({\fs16 {\i f}})}={{\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 \u8722?,{\i i}})}{{\u948*}{\i v}}{{\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 +,{\i f}})}+{{\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 \u8722?,{\i i}})}{{\u948*}{\i v}}{{\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 \u8722?,{\i f}})}+{{\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 +,{\i i}})}{{\u948*}{\i v}}{{\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 +,{\i f}})}+{{\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 +,{\i i}})}{{\u948*}{\i v}}{{\u968*}\\s\\up({\fs16 \u8722?,{\i f}})}}}{\fldrslt }}
\tab{\b0 ({\*\bkmkstart BMdistortedbornexpansion}12{\*\bkmkend BMdistortedbornexpansion})}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 Where {{\u948*}{\i v}} describes a perturbation on the scattering potential that the incident wave experiences. If we expand the left-hand side in the integral notation we get: {\par
